<subSubSection id="2214C389E8EA39770000D293015BD527" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="1A41725FB865BD6E3DED339E6D08295C" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ED33D45F32E38FA4EEAEED03D5ACE055" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">
Male: A medium sized (9-11 mm) mason bee with a black body covered in yellow-brown hair and short antennae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4AD9C8E8F82BD0601414A99A8336B183" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F6661788" captionText="Figure 2. Hoplitis papaveris (Latreille, 1799) (Mertert, specimen MNHNL 21866). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view showing abdomen curvature; c. Abdomen, showing the two terminal lobules of tergite 7; d. Detailed view of the propodeum (shiny surface). Scale bars = 1 mm. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501348" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">2</figureCitation>
a). Tergite 6 is strongly curved (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="878A36EEB59EAD43C865B5E1A24C744D" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F6661788" captionText="Figure 2. Hoplitis papaveris (Latreille, 1799) (Mertert, specimen MNHNL 21866). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view showing abdomen curvature; c. Abdomen, showing the two terminal lobules of tergite 7; d. Detailed view of the propodeum (shiny surface). Scale bars = 1 mm. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501348" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">2</figureCitation>
b) and tergite 7 presents a characteristic forked edge (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="19523D727E057FAF1C4FC8CCC6ECC6B8" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F6661788" captionText="Figure 2. Hoplitis papaveris (Latreille, 1799) (Mertert, specimen MNHNL 21866). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view showing abdomen curvature; c. Abdomen, showing the two terminal lobules of tergite 7; d. Detailed view of the propodeum (shiny surface). Scale bars = 1 mm. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501348" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">2</figureCitation>
c). The midfield part of the propodeum has a polished terminal surface (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="3CF012198CDF6596175C3F0A3793ADD2" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F6661788" captionText="Figure 2. Hoplitis papaveris (Latreille, 1799) (Mertert, specimen MNHNL 21866). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view showing abdomen curvature; c. Abdomen, showing the two terminal lobules of tergite 7; d. Detailed view of the propodeum (shiny surface). Scale bars = 1 mm. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501348" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">2</figureCitation>
d).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ECC5D7F65E4FBD31276D5A8B29153925" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Voucher specimen (MNHNL21866): Adult male. Body length of 8.8 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9A4D21E554DB97B0B5B2D537279D51BF" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="E8C525133EB909F30A2A3B164584A49B" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Ecology</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FE1ED97FEC4F3DBD20AE0D5C4CF40770" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">
A ground-nesting bee that builds its nest in sandy soil, using pieces of poppy petals (
<taxonomicName id="A42A4B9120531CBB555E299B934446E2" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Papaver" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Papaver rhoeas" order="Papaverales" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="rhoeas">
<emphasis id="DD6267A4B21E491894FCA51E1D84CE35" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Papaver rhoeas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) to line the brood cells (
<bibRefCitation id="C19197B592E6C8899C79C56AFEA42111" author="Guenter, R." journalOrPublisher="bembiX" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" pagination="22 - 30" refId="B6643214" refString="Guenter, R., 1997. Beobachtungen zur Mohnbiene (Osmia papaveris). bembiX 8: 22 - 30" title="Beobachtungen zur Mohnbiene (Osmia papaveris)" volume="8" year="1997">
<normalizedToken id="C39BA0D8C28497BBD90F2995A3FB1D2E" originalValue="GÃ¼nter">Guenter</normalizedToken>
1997
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="6495CD8FADAB7937C483E399914EBCDF" author="Amiet, F." journalOrPublisher="Fauna Helvetica 9. Apidae 4: Anthidium, Chelostoma, Coelioxys, Dioxys, Heriades, Lithurgus, Megachile, Osmia, Stelis" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6643121" refString="Amiet, F., Herrmann, M., Mueller, A., Neumeyer, R., 2004. . Fauna Helvetica 9. Apidae 4: Anthidium, Chelostoma, Coelioxys, Dioxys, Heriades, Lithurgus, Megachile, Osmia, Stelis 9" volume="9" year="2004">Amiet et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
). Its flight season spans from late May to mid July (
<bibRefCitation id="C8951989FFFC7AD79B76B43AB5DF62B8" author="Amiet, F." journalOrPublisher="Fauna Helvetica 9. Apidae 4: Anthidium, Chelostoma, Coelioxys, Dioxys, Heriades, Lithurgus, Megachile, Osmia, Stelis" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6643121" refString="Amiet, F., Herrmann, M., Mueller, A., Neumeyer, R., 2004. . Fauna Helvetica 9. Apidae 4: Anthidium, Chelostoma, Coelioxys, Dioxys, Heriades, Lithurgus, Megachile, Osmia, Stelis 9" volume="9" year="2004">Amiet et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8213A7E950468EC3111F822E94608D8F" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="71924B60EBFAD2FB7D0904402099E705" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Conservation</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ED675E90EE0C9FFD56BC857DBE92B277" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">
<taxonomicName id="60008A35194601DDCD6D031690037A42" baseAuthorityName="Latreille" baseAuthorityYear="1799" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Hoplitis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hoplitis papaveris" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="papaveris">
<emphasis id="15542E65FB49581F569D813550C82668" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Hoplitis papaveris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is classified under the IUCN category &quot;Least Concern (LC)&quot; (
<bibRefCitation id="3A3BEC8FB7CA18884BF1CB851996A89C" author="Nieto, A." journalOrPublisher="Luxembourg: Publications Office of the European Union" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6643307" refString="Nieto, A., Roberts, S. P.M., Kemp, J., Rasmont, P., Kuhlmann, M., Garcia Criado, M., Biesmeijer, J. C., Bogusch, P., Dathe, H. H., De la Rua, P., De Meulemeester, T., Dehon, M., Dewulf, A., Ortiz-Sanchez, F. J., Lhomme, P., Pauly, A., Potts, S. G., Praz, C., Quaranta, M., Radchenko, V. G., Scheuchl, E., Smit, J., Straka, J., Terzo, M., Tomozii, B., Window, J., Michez, D., 2014. European Red List of bees. Luxembourg: Publications Office of the European Union" title="European Red List of bees" year="2014">Nieto et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
), but it is listed in the National Red Lists and Red Data Books of the Czech Republic, Germany, the Netherlands and Switzerland, emphasising that further research is needed regarding the species population sizes, trends and threats (
<bibRefCitation id="D12E8BF331CBFFF9B481D39101B4790A" author="Lane, Meredith A." journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6643279" refString="Lhomme P. Hoplitis papaveris. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2014 https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/19199070/21154652 2020-08-11T00:00:00+03:00" year="1996">Lhomme 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
